1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:12,000
We're rolling.

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:19,000
Today is Wednesday, September 14, 2011.

4
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:23,000
My name is... I'm here in some voices, John Hume.

5
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:26,000
But we'll finish the intro and then we'll pause.

6
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:32,000
Okay. Wednesday, September 14, 2011.

7
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:39,000
My name is Joe Mosnier, the Southern oral history program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

8
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:41,000
I'm with the videographer John Bishop.

9
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:51,000
We are in St. Augustine, Florida at the Bayfront Hilton Hotel to do interviews for the Civil Rights History Project,

10
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:59,000
which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

11
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:09,000
And broadly speaking, our host on this visit has been local civil rights pioneer Dr. Robert B. Hayling.

12
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:15,000
And Dr. Hayling, thank you for all that you've done to make our visit possible and we're really looking forward to the conversation.

13
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:24,000
Thank you and we're so indebted to all of you who have made this possible.

14
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:25,000
Thank you so much.

15
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:28,000
Well, we're delighted to have a chance to visit.

16
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:35,000
Let me ask you to start today by just talking a little bit about your family in Tallahassee.

17
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:37,000
Coming up.

18
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:44,000
Yes. I was born in Tallahassee, Florida, November 20, 1929.

19
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:59,000
My father was an instructor on the faculty of Florida A&M, which was college at that time in the Industrial Education Department.

20
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:03,000
His specialty was tailoring.

21
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:14,000
And my mother, for many, many years in our developmental years, was a homemaker.

22
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:22,000
But she was out of New Orleans, Louisiana, of Creole extraction.

23
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:26,000
My father was from Grenada.

24
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:33,000
And therefore, he had to acquire his citizenship and all.

25
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:43,000
And he taught at Florida A&M for Generalize, because some said 32 and some say 34.

26
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:46,000
So I say 33 years.

27
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:50,000
There were four children in the family.

28
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:55,000
I have an older brother, Charles Hayling Jr.

29
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:58,000
I was 18 months older than I am.

30
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:04,000
I had a sister who is deceased now, Francis Hayling.

31
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:14,000
And then my youngest sister, Yvonne Hayling Clark, is now retired living in Sarasota, Florida.

32
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:25,000
We all acquired our basic education of college through Florida A&M.

33
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:35,000
And then went on every child in the family acquired an advanced degree beyond a college degree.

34
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:43,000
And the other three were involved in education and guidance and so forth.

35
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:55,000
And I was fortunate enough to go into the Air Force as a college graduate on August of 1951.

36
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:09,000
After three months of basic training in the Air Force, at Lackland Air Force Base, San Antonio, Texas,

37
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:19,000
I was admitted to the hospital, or we said medical assisting training program,

38
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:26,000
that the Air Force had a Sheppard Air Force Base, Wichita Falls, Texas.

39
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:38,000
And after I completed that training, I was admitted to the staff of the local hospital on the Air Force Base.

40
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:43,000
And the Air Force Base has a medical technician.

41
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:58,000
And they asked her to allow me time and to acquire the knowledge as a laboratory technician to make application to Officer Candidate School.

42
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:11,000
And I was fortunate enough to be accepted and graduated from the Air Force Academy's Officer Candidate School.

43
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:14,000
No, but Academy, we can cross that out.

44
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:22,000
It's just the Air Force Officer Candidate School across our Academy.

45
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:27,000
Yes, because we have the Air Force Academy 9 Colorado Springs.

46
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:41,000
But, and commissioned as a second lieutenant in the class of 52D, which was December of 1952.

47
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:54,000
And as Lackwood Havett, I was assigned to an extremely good assignment of Rev. Thomas A. Wright Sr Patterson Air Force Base Daytono Hyle,

48
00:05:54,000 --> 00:06:04,000
as a Aeromedical Researcher and the Biomedical Laboratory that I was assigned to.

49
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:10,000
And my department field was toxicology.

50
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:21,000
And I will research ran from forensic to biological to all forms of toxicology.

51
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:37,000
And I enjoy that work immensely and was way out of my class because as a lieutenant, those kinds of assignments were stranger than Hens' teeth.

52
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:49,000
And that's a plumb to be assigned to Rev. Thomas A. Wright Sr Patterson Air Force Base with all the in-depth and high-type research that was going on.

53
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:58,000
And many times, all my peers were captain's majors in lieutenant colonels and on up the line.

54
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:08,000
But after a period of time, I had called out a space for a first lieutenant to participate in all.

55
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:19,000
And to my chagrin after being accepted to dental school and asking for an early release from the Air Force to attend dental school,

56
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:32,000
I was counted off it with an early promotion to captain if I would consent to stay and continue to work that I was involved in, said no way.

57
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:38,000
All my life, I had always wanted to be a dentist or a veterinarian.

58
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:44,000
And once I was accepted to dental school, there was no turning back.

59
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:57,000
Even though in the interim period, I had married my college sweetheart and brought her as a school teacher from Miami, Florida to Dayton, Ohio.

60
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:17,000
And we enjoyed a year of whatever because she was the homemaker as the wife and had the privileges to the office club and to the can't come to the cemetery for shopping and everything else.

61
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:22,000
And we also had acquired a box of puppy, a dog.

62
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:26,000
And we named the dog, Mandana.

63
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:33,000
And we enjoyed training, watching the dog grow and training the dog and all the activities.

64
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:50,000
And she had real misgivings about giving up that line of livelihood and also status of living because we were still in the various segregated phases of America.

65
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:57,000
And even though we went Ohio and everything else, we didn't feel extreme pressures or whatever.

66
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:09,000
But we knew that the wave of change was sweeping over the USA and she consented.

67
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:14,000
Even though we had to break up the apartment and everything else and all.

68
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:20,000
And she went back to Miami to live with her parents and everything else.

69
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:24,000
And spent some time in Tallahassee with my parents.

70
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:36,000
And while we were getting adjusted because everything was so school started in 55, September.

71
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:38,000
And at Meharry.

72
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:43,000
And we had to kind of break down everything else and whatever.

73
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:46,000
And get her situated and all.

74
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:52,000
And then get me into Nashville and it ensured order.

75
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:56,000
But we made the necessary adjustments.

76
00:09:56,000 --> 00:10:09,000
And I found that the adjustment to studying took a period of time and especially with my peer groups.

77
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:19,000
Recently out of college and many had advanced degrees in everything in the various medical fields.

78
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:40,000
And so I fortunately had the honor of graduating with a class where one of our top, top scholars in my class eventually rose to be the dean of the dental school at Meharry and all.

79
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:43,000
And so Fred Fielder

80
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:48,000
And now he's retired in everything.

81
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:53,000
But that's in many of the other class members.

82
00:10:53,000 --> 00:11:00,000
And so we had a team of tremendous honors and credits in their chosen field.

83
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:13,000
And several went on to be part time entrepreneurs and financial consultants and things like that.

84
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:16,000
And so we asked about Turok.

85
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:19,000
We're very short.

86
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:22,000
Quick adjustment to the microphones.

87
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:26,000
Dr. Henry, I wanted to ask that there's so much that we could spend time on.

88
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:29,000
I would love to hear about your experience in dental school.

89
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:32,000
But since our focus broadly today is civil rights.

90
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:41,000
Let me ask about you were in Nashville during some very interesting years and became involved with some folks who would like yourself.

91
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:51,000
And I wonder if you could talk a little bit about Nashville and how you became engaged in that kind of work and activism.

92
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:53,000
Yes.

93
00:11:53,000 --> 00:12:05,000
As a student, I was aware of the civil rights activities of Nashville but not intimately involved.

94
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:15,000
But my jurisprudence or dental law instructor was Z. Alexander Looby.

95
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:30,000
And it ended up that he was the lead attorney for the desegregation of the Nashville of the Tennessee area public schools.

96
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:40,000
And it produced the occasion of having his home dynamite it.

97
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:48,000
And he was on a street adjacent to the dormitory that I was living in at Meharry.

98
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:57,000
And the morning that they dynamited the front part of his house blew out windows of the dormitory.

99
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:01,000
Some windows in the dormitory that I was housed in.

100
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:08,000
It happened that the wing that I was in of the dormitory was further away from his house.

101
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:12,000
I can't claim that it blew out the window in my room.

102
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:18,000
But I was a marshal in the dormitory and so forth.

103
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:30,000
And therefore we were concerned about the glass clean up and getting the windows covered and everything else because it was the exact date I cannot say.

104
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:40,000
But being school time school started in September I can finish the exact date I have that with me.

105
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:58,000
But the leaders of the movement that I ended up making a acquaintance with were John Lewis, Diane Nash, C.T. Vivian,

106
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:05,000
La Theat, I have to get La Theat's first name.

107
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:10,000
And James Bevel.

108
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:22,000
And all of these ended up being leaders in latter years in the civil rights movement and all.

109
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:27,000
And even James Bevel and Diane Nash married.

110
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:34,000
They divorced later on but I think they produced a family out of that siblings I should.

111
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:39,000
I produced children out of that union and all.

112
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:44,000
And I had to get in excuse.

113
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:51,000
I don't remember now whether I went to the infirmary for illness or I slipped out of a class or whatever.

114
00:14:51,000 --> 00:15:15,000
But I had to be part of the march because students from this university, Tennessee and I University in Nashville, had a April 19, 1960 silent march on Nashville City Hall for a protest with the dynamite of Z. Alexander Looby.

115
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:19,000
And that was a great day and everything else.

116
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:42,000
And I think it brought the powers that be in Nashville to their senses that something had to be done and it went on that action or even I would almost say school desegregation went further rather than to be resisted or set back or anything like that.

117
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:50,000
Was that the first occasion when you would have taken an active role in civil rights demonstration?

118
00:15:50,000 --> 00:16:02,000
I would have to say and check on the years and times but my visits back to Tallahassee, Revan CK Steel.

119
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:10,000
And then we had Patricia Stephens Due and Priscilla Stephens.

120
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:31,000
There were two movements in Tallahassee going on, one dealt with the desegregation of the movie theaters and I think restaurants and CK Steel led the movement to the transportation system, the buses, the bus system in Tallahassee.

121
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:39,000
And his movement was so powerful that it led to the bankruptcy of the bus system and all.

122
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:50,000
And now at the bus station in Tallahassee, there's a life-size monument of CK Steel for all the world to see.

123
00:16:50,000 --> 00:17:03,000
And I have also made the acquaintance of Patricia and her husband who was John Due who came here as a young attorney to help us in synodistine.

124
00:17:03,000 --> 00:17:18,000
And they went on to achieve prominence in the civil rights field and they also wrote a book, a cult wrote a book called Freedom in the Family.

125
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:46,000
And to this day they are still speaking and touring and attending conferences and meetings and speaking of their ventures because the most prominent one that I remember, these two young ladies were housed in a jail setup in Tallahassee with wire-thensing around them.

126
00:17:46,000 --> 00:18:05,000
In a setup where they had access to I think a Camo facility and a Facebook but no privacy.

127
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:23,000
And they had to guard each other, take off their clothes and shield the other one as best possible to try to retain some sense of dignity when taking care of their personal needs and all.

128
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:44,000
And I still don't know at this time how a city like Tallahassee, because Tallahassee was the seat at that time of Florida State University for women and the University of Florida in Gainesville was for men.

129
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:57,000
And I should say for white women and white men and all. And then we had Florida and in college at that time in Tallahassee and was the capital.

130
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:17,000
So we weren't talking about some backwards out, back type community and all. But there were extreme battles and resistance for Tallahassee for complying and to racial desegregation.

131
00:19:17,000 --> 00:19:34,000
But all of these magnificent people and Reverend C.K. Steele and Reverend Dan Speed made trips from Tallahassee to come to our freedom rallies in St. Augustine.

132
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:49,000
And many times spoke either as the principal speakers or auxiliary speakers for the various rallies and naturally they sent us financial support.

133
00:19:49,000 --> 00:20:07,000
Tell me if you were about how the experience in Nashville and those years you were in dental school, how it shaped your emerging sense of what role of any you might have in ongoing civil rights activities.

134
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:27,000
And I had never had this point in time had no idea, never ever thought about leading movement or participating. Naturally I was a 10 rallies and I was a proud NAACP and things like that.

135
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:31,000
How did you make your choice to come to St. Augustine?

136
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:51,000
I had Florida had a educational system set up because Florida did not have dental schools. And at that time the white students from Florida went to Emory University University in Atlanta, the dental school.

137
00:20:51,000 --> 00:21:08,000
And the Meharry was given a supplement or bonus of a thousand dollars per year for any black male or female attending dental school from the state of Florida.

138
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:31,000
And therefore I think along with my service record or academic record of what have helped me gain entrance to the Harry because the school in addition to all of my tuition and all and then I would also have to admit because of my service in the F.A.S. I had the benefit of the GI bill.

139
00:21:31,000 --> 00:21:59,000
And that made my educational finances at my Harry a bit able to carry itself or at least not put me in an extreme hole that many students have today for having to borrow money or make student loans and so forth.

140
00:21:59,000 --> 00:22:22,000
I also had the good fortune of working in New York each summer as a sky cap for the Port Authority of NY/NJ. And I was a sky cap at Newark Airport from 12 o'clock at night until 8 o'clock in the morning.

141
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:47,000
And from June until Labor Day I worked many times six and seven days a week. And in the daytime I served lunch or dinner at a big two story restaurant in New York and Sheepshead Bay which is on the way to Coney Island.

142
00:22:47,000 --> 00:23:04,000
And this magnificent seafood restaurant and from anywhere from four to four thirty to five o'clock in the evenings until 8 thirty or nine o'clock at night caught the subway up to Grand Central Station and the bus over the New York Airport.

143
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:20,000
And this was enhanced and that my relatives, my father's sister on Hester and other relatives and all gave us accommodations for living because my wife came up to be with me.

144
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:37,000
And she enjoyed playing the role of the wife because we had a system that once I got to Grand Central Station I would call them and they would get my back water and everything else ready and all and my breakfast.

145
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:53,000
When I came in I had breakfast and had a good hot bath to go to bed to get in some sleep time between arriving in Brooklyn and having to be at the restaurant for four to four thirty in the evenings.

146
00:23:53,000 --> 00:24:04,000
But this restaurant and that experience was so magnificent because they used between a hundred to a hundred and fifty waiters at a time.

147
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:10,000
This was a massive place and they were world famous for seafood.

148
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:16,000
They owned their own shrimp boats and fishing boats and everything else.

149
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:31,000
And many blacks especially young black males on the road up because how would university in Washington D.C., furnished law students and medical and dental students.

150
00:24:31,000 --> 00:24:44,000
And then I don't remember yes two or three of my Harry students also joined us as waiters in New York.

151
00:24:44,000 --> 00:24:49,000
But I don't think many of them stuck throughout the entire summer.

152
00:24:49,000 --> 00:25:03,000
I just turned over at this restaurant with so if you had a buddy system and could get in through the hiring mechanism you could work weekends or strategic times and so forth.

153
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:11,000
Let me bring you back to that was a strategy obviously for surviving financially during the dental school years.

154
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:16,000
How did you make your choice to come towards San Otas thing?

155
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:30,000
I had acquired a convertible books wagon red bottom with a white top and we had an additional automobile.

156
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:48,000
So after taking the dental exam in Florida for the efficiency or what is called the dental board exam July the 4th weekend of 1960.

157
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:55,000
And there's a time period where the schools have to be evaluated and everything else and all.

158
00:25:55,000 --> 00:26:01,000
And where you would know whether you will permit it to practice dentistry in the state of Florida.

159
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:17,000
So I started on the east coast of Florida when all the way down through visiting the various cities were in the space that had black dentists and all down to when all the way to Key West.

160
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:33,000
And when they came back on the west side up through the Sarasota and then into Tampa and all of that area and then went all the way out to Pensacola and came back to Tallahassee.

161
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:40,000
And so it ended up of the cities that I evaluated.

162
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:54,000
Soon Augustine had a very prominent dentist who had met a tragic automobile accident encountered early death and all root off Gordon.

163
00:26:54,000 --> 00:26:59,000
And his office facilities were available.

164
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:16,000
And in Panama City two brothers, the Buford brothers, one was a dentist and the other was a physician and they had built a nice office facility in Panama City.

165
00:27:16,000 --> 00:27:30,000
And after evaluating and all, I being located in Panama City, I would have been 90 miles from Pensacola or 90 miles from Tallahassee.

166
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:41,000
So I was sitting out there in the panhandle and what had in somehow I am one because even in Soon Augustine and I hate to admit this.

167
00:27:41,000 --> 00:28:07,000
But I used to get in my car and drive at night after I had finished my office hours to Jacksonville to some of the night spots or some of the late night restaurants just to meet civilization because one of my first comments through the various people was they rolled up the sidewalks in Soon Augustine at sundown.

168
00:28:07,000 --> 00:28:20,000
And which is totally true, I found they drew the curtains and the people had their affairs or whatever parties inside that the general public didn't know about.

169
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:43,000
But it was a wonderful thing to have Mrs. Gordon, the widow of Dr. Gordon, except me and also offer to introduce me to her constituency or his older patients and all.

170
00:28:43,000 --> 00:28:52,000
And so in December of 60, we had a housewarming and everything else.

171
00:28:52,000 --> 00:29:03,000
And it was a bit delayed or put off and all to a certain point because Dr. Gordon was a chained cigar smoker.

172
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:15,000
And the entire office reaped of the very expensive Cuban cigars that he bought by the carton.

173
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:29,000
And he was a gregarious kind of charismatic fellow spoke three languages and dabbled in two others.

174
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:38,000
And his practice was 50 to 60 or 60 to 70 percent white.

175
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:45,000
And I kind of inherited that kind of goodwill and all.

176
00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:58,000
So my practice started off with a boom because many people came in saying that they hadn't been to the dentist in the two years or 18 month period.

177
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:04,000
And so when the office was non-functional, so that made it quite well.

178
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:21,000
I was also accepted as the city jail dentist, the county jail dentist and the state prison-formed dentist of the county of St. Johns and the city of St. Augustine.

179
00:30:21,000 --> 00:30:32,000
Now it ends up that that wasn't totally because of my professional capabilities and all.

180
00:30:32,000 --> 00:30:49,000
But many of the white dentists, because if they brought you patients from this jail, the attending officer had to have a side on, a pistol on his waist.

181
00:30:49,000 --> 00:30:58,000
And many patients and even the nurses in the doctor's office felt uncomfortable with that.

182
00:30:58,000 --> 00:31:05,000
And so I, being a start-up dentist, blocked off periods of time.

183
00:31:05,000 --> 00:31:16,000
I didn't refuse walk-ins, but I scheduled no patients at the time that they would meet in my reception room going or coming or being there.

184
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:29,000
Because even when I had the patient in the treatment room, the officer, we would leave the doors open and so forth so they could hear what was going on and what was taking place.

185
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:38,000
But they generally stayed out in the reception room, was stood in the doorway and all with the treatment that was being administered.

186
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:44,000
Many of the deputies came to me as private patients and whatever.

187
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:54,000
And I don't mind saying now because of their contact and everything, their general treatment was usually on the house.

188
00:31:54,000 --> 00:32:10,000
And even to the point that the sheriff, L.O. Davis, who was also a change cigar smoker, had been to my office as a patient.

189
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:18,000
And you mentioned that you typically did not charge white law enforcement.

190
00:32:18,000 --> 00:32:29,000
I think anyway, it was set up in St. Augustine because of the economy of St. Augustine.

191
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:36,000
I had to devise a self-finance payment system.

192
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:43,000
So very few of my patients paid, she always said, out of pocket cash.

193
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:58,000
So if they made a deposit and started some payment on a treatment plan that we had rigged up for them, we would expect monthly payments or whenever they said they could afford to pay.

194
00:32:58,000 --> 00:33:15,000
So I definitely would not say they didn't pay anything, but they knew that there was nobody breathing down their necks or any hardship about finances for the various treatments that they required.

195
00:33:15,000 --> 00:33:24,000
To the point that many of them brought the wives and their children, especially for check-ups and for dental evaluations.

196
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:32,000
I may have not put my question very clearly. I thought you said that you didn't charge white law enforcement as a group and wondered if there was a reason for that.

197
00:33:32,000 --> 00:33:36,000
We only had one black deputy sheriff.

198
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:45,000
And we had a black who freed waters who patrolled a black community, Lincolnville, at night.

199
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:51,000
He was permitted to have a pistol, but he had civilian clothes.

200
00:33:51,000 --> 00:33:59,000
So did there anything coercive about the arrangement with someone like L.O. Davis coming to your business that you would have been worried about?

201
00:33:59,000 --> 00:34:11,000
Not at the time. I didn't become, so we say, radio active until I got involved with silver rights.

202
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:14,000
Before then, I was a good fellow.

203
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:28,000
I was just, I wondered if maybe you were trying to suggest that you were in effect had no real choice but to provide service to people like L.O. Davis without charge.

204
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:36,000
Never, ever, no arrangement, no formal arrangement was ever made or anything.

205
00:34:36,000 --> 00:34:46,000
Definitely, or it was known ahead of time that whatever treatment minister was on the house or whatever.

206
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:56,000
Well, let me move on to the question of between you're settling in and opening your practice in late 1960 and all of what will begin to happen in 63.

207
00:34:56,000 --> 00:35:07,000
Can you tell me the story of how in that span of a couple of years you moved towards what would become the prominent leadership position in local movement?

208
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:25,000
Well, nothing was structured. I'd heard later that the NAACP since we moved under the banner of the NAACP had sent me to St. Augustine to lead the movement and so forth and all.

209
00:35:25,000 --> 00:35:48,000
Well, if the NAACP could ever arrange to send a professional person to an area or to help establish a movement or a chapter or something, they would really be way above the status that I knew of.

210
00:35:48,000 --> 00:36:14,000
I had made certain contacts within the community and gotten to know many of the young people either as adolescents, youngsters who I had encountered in my visits and opening relationships with various organizations within the city and all.

211
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:43,000
They had also started a movement, our general Edwards mentioned yesterday that they had been meeting and it was under the advisory ship of Reverend Thomas Rev. Thomas A. Wright Sr, who was a local minister, Baptist minister and also an instructor at the Black College, Florida Memorial College in St. Augustine.

212
00:36:43,000 --> 00:37:04,000
His wife was an elementary school teacher but once they got started as youngsters as a youth group in the protest movement, the establishment looked into it and found out that Reverend Rev. Thomas A. Wright Sr was the advisor.

213
00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:20,000
His wife was fired from the school system and pressure was put on the college to get him to cease his sponsorship of the Youth Council and all.

214
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:36,000
When he refused to do that, he had to leave St. Augustine and move his family to Gainesville, Florida. He acquired a good Mount Carmel Baptist Church in Gainesville, Florida.

215
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:53,000
Mrs. Rev. Thomas A. Wright Sr went over to Gainesville and acquired a job as a school teacher and as luck would have it, his oldest daughter was the first black to integrate the high school of Gainesville, Florida.

216
00:37:53,000 --> 00:38:18,000
He kept on with the movement even though he had to leave St. Augustine. A delegation of youngsters came to my office and ended up asking me that they had lost their advisor, would I consider advising them and helping them with the movement that they had started.

217
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:29,000
At that time, as far as I know, it was only picketing and demonstrating and carrying picket signs and things and all.

218
00:38:29,000 --> 00:38:31,000
So it's 1963?

219
00:38:31,000 --> 00:38:32,000
Yes.

220
00:38:32,000 --> 00:38:59,000
The management and the owners of the various shops were not moved. In other words, they tolerated. Naturally, many of them had to be instructed as to how to stay on the sidewalk, how to keep moving and only certain numbers would be allowed per establishment and all.

221
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:05,000
We made a valid attempt to follow all of the rules.

222
00:39:05,000 --> 00:39:17,000
Why did you fill in my prescriptions for all pain medication or anything else that I would prescribe?

223
00:39:17,000 --> 00:39:34,000
The relationship was very good over the telephone and all. I admit now looking back that I don't think I had ever made an in-person visit to those various establishments.

224
00:39:34,000 --> 00:39:51,000
But even then, it would have been a walk-in and a walk-out because I don't think I was to that point of trying as my young people eventually got around to seeing he wanted was a hamburger and a coke.

225
00:39:51,000 --> 00:40:10,000
But that was what we had to devise for the news media in the end because at the lunch counter, when you sat down, if the waistress asked you, what can I serve you or what do you want?

226
00:40:10,000 --> 00:40:23,000
They would usually say, I want to order a hamburger and a coke and that was acceptable. But as I said at the time, we had no great overall structure.

227
00:40:23,000 --> 00:40:37,000
I don't ever remember receiving any instructions on how to carry out a movement from the NAACP, especially a youth movement and all.

228
00:40:37,000 --> 00:40:44,000
Did you talk in these days with the women who were heading up the community chapter of the NAACP?

229
00:40:44,000 --> 00:41:04,000
Yes, yes. A lady by the name of Fannie Fulwood was the president of the local NAACP chapter. And Mrs. Elizabeth Hawthorne, I think it's Mrs. Elizabeth Hawthorne, was the secretary for the NAACP.

230
00:41:04,000 --> 00:41:22,000
And she offered herself as a secretary for our youth council and all. And Mrs. Elizabeth Hawthorne wrote a bicycle and she lived on the west, on the north side of town.

231
00:41:22,000 --> 00:41:34,000
We were considered on the south side and she would ride across the city even though she had a mental, a bad deformity.

232
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:49,000
And back in those days, that ailment was referred to as hunchback. And she had a beautiful personality and did excellent secretary work.

233
00:41:49,000 --> 00:42:18,000
And we were so fortunate to have her because she was my stabilizer at the time. Mrs. Fullerwood, through the regional director of the NAACP, a lady by the name of Ruby Hurley, who was headquartered in Atlanta, had gotten wind of the movement.

234
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:42,000
In St. Augustine and Word had filtered back up through the line of communication that the youth had ideas of stepping up the non-responsive picketing and demonstrating methods that they had been using.

235
00:42:42,000 --> 00:43:02,000
And they intervened and said that the NAACP was not ready to take on a major movement in St. Augustine because of the size and the economy of St. Augustine.

236
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:16,000
Well, to counterbalance this, the city of St. Augustine was getting ready to celebrate the 400th anniversary of the founding of the city.

237
00:43:16,000 --> 00:43:33,000
And the federal government had appropriated $400,000 to the city to help celebrate and commemorate the entire anniversary period and all.

238
00:43:34,000 --> 00:43:57,000
Not one black, even though at the time the black population was somewhere close to 20% of the city had been appointed to any of the committees involved with the complete year of celebrating the 400th anniversary.

239
00:43:58,000 --> 00:44:11,000
And that was a wake-up call to the racial attitudes of St. Augustine because we had black principals of the various schools.

240
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:20,000
We had a black who was superintendent of the black schools, Mrs. Reddick and all.

241
00:44:20,000 --> 00:44:49,000
And so, and then we had black professors at the college, Florida Memorial College, and the president, Dr. Perrier, was considered an erudite, educated person who would have been very appropriately appointed to any committees and so forth.

242
00:44:51,000 --> 00:45:15,000
Well, we finally came down to the fact that the city was having a big anniversary dinner, a complete day of celebration that included the ambassador from Spain, a visit by the vice president of the United States.

243
00:45:16,000 --> 00:45:35,000
And naturally the two senators and representatives, the governor and his cabinet and all, we had many, many dignitaries in St. Augustine for that particular day to celebrate and attend the dinner, the big formal dinner.

244
00:45:36,000 --> 00:45:39,000
And this would have been late spring 1963.

245
00:45:39,000 --> 00:45:40,000
Yes.

246
00:45:40,000 --> 00:45:57,000
At the Ponce de Leon Hotel, which is a big magnificent edifice that was so suited because they had a grand ballroom dinner room and all.

247
00:45:57,000 --> 00:46:16,000
So we fired all, we, I fired all for that, to the vice president, to ask him not to attend this segregated function and all because of the exclusion of the black citizenry.

248
00:46:17,000 --> 00:46:38,000
And it generated enough heat that Lyndon B. Johnson at the time sent in his representative, a fellow by the name of George Reedy, about at least a week ahead of the appropriated time for the dinner and all.

249
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:51,000
And he made many visits to my office, met with many of the other people involved and what have you, because the news media had gotten wind of the letter and all.

250
00:46:51,000 --> 00:47:07,000
And they could see that the pressure was being generated because we had offered the idea that we were going to demonstrate a boycott or do something for this.

251
00:47:07,000 --> 00:47:13,000
Because of the exclusion of the black citizens of St. Augustine.

252
00:47:13,000 --> 00:47:36,000
Well, Mr. Reedy and being neo-fights in this tremendous pressure game, convinced us that the vice president was interested and had read the letter and all and had agreed that if we did not pick it up demonstrate or do anything to distribute it.

253
00:47:36,000 --> 00:47:51,000
And we had to do anything to disrupt the flow and the feeling of the city at that time that he would do his best to see that something was done about this.

254
00:47:51,000 --> 00:48:04,000
We had enough sense, I guess, to say, well, will we be attending? They went run ahead of us and said yes.

255
00:48:04,000 --> 00:48:15,000
So, six, I was either six or eight that they agreed could attend. And we thought at the time we were going to be seated in the Grand Ballroom.

256
00:48:15,000 --> 00:48:25,000
But when we arrived, we were seated in an all-cove that looked down on the Grand Ballroom.

257
00:48:25,000 --> 00:48:37,000
And the only whites that we had the dinner with were the Secret Service and FBI agents.

258
00:48:37,000 --> 00:48:41,000
Now, many didn't identify themselves one way or the other.

259
00:48:41,000 --> 00:48:52,000
And I may have to check with others, but I think Mr. Reedy stayed and ate with us.

260
00:48:52,000 --> 00:49:05,000
And we were still such neophytes in this high pressure game that we agreed to the next morning of a meeting.

261
00:49:05,000 --> 00:49:09,000
And we thought we were going to meet with the City Commission and the Mayor.

262
00:49:09,000 --> 00:49:12,000
That had been your request and that was the barbed wire.

263
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:13,000
Yes.

264
00:49:13,000 --> 00:49:18,000
And that was agreed to, we thought.

265
00:49:18,000 --> 00:49:25,000
We came again dressed in our little Sunday go-to meeting clothes.

266
00:49:25,000 --> 00:49:29,000
And we got to the designated place.

267
00:49:29,000 --> 00:49:35,000
And there was the Mayor's Secretary and her tape recorder.

268
00:49:35,000 --> 00:49:44,000
Not a single commissioner, not the Mayor, and not one representative from Washington.

269
00:49:44,000 --> 00:49:45,000
So no, Mr. Reedy?

270
00:49:45,000 --> 00:49:50,000
No, Mr. Reedy or anyone representing him.

271
00:49:50,000 --> 00:49:54,000
So we had really been outfoxed.

272
00:49:54,000 --> 00:49:58,000
But we still didn't know any better.

273
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:12,000
Each member presented their name and address and their position and the various amounts of their involvement with the request.

274
00:50:12,000 --> 00:50:41,000
Because all main requests at the time was a biracial committee to hear and at least give the agreed black citizens the permission to air their grievances before a formal city board or whatever.

275
00:50:42,000 --> 00:50:51,000
The Secretary played the tape so that we knew we were on tape and everything.

276
00:50:51,000 --> 00:50:56,000
And thank this for coming and we left.

277
00:50:56,000 --> 00:51:07,000
To this day, as far as I know, we never ever received a response to that request.

278
00:51:07,000 --> 00:51:25,000
The outfoxed just another way that they took the black policeman who functioned in the Lincolnville, the black community at night, as the police force in that area, who wore civilian clothes.

279
00:51:25,000 --> 00:51:31,000
But he was allowed to have a pistol. They call a side arm.

280
00:51:31,000 --> 00:51:51,000
He dressed him in a police uniform and a cap and all and put him right downtown in Augustine around what was known then as the Old Slave Market, which is a main traffic area directing traffic on that day.

281
00:51:51,000 --> 00:51:57,000
The news reporter broke down the door at my office coming in and knocked at him and knocked at him.

282
00:51:57,000 --> 00:52:03,000
I thought you said you didn't have a black policeman on the force and all.

283
00:52:03,000 --> 00:52:09,000
That was the day of the dinner and he had a presence in the city.

284
00:52:09,000 --> 00:52:20,000
So that was an attempt to see that we had made a false request because they had a black policeman and all.

285
00:52:20,000 --> 00:52:30,000
You soon will become quite strategic then in your subsequent decisions about how to proceed and carry the movement forward.

286
00:52:30,000 --> 00:52:42,000
I'd love to have you talk about how you were feeling after that George Reedy episode and how you decided to recalculate and move forward.

287
00:52:42,000 --> 00:52:49,000
I wish I could say we had a battle plan or strategy.

288
00:52:49,000 --> 00:53:09,000
But many times with the various defeats that we encountered, we had to gather our forces and go back to our think tanks and everything because within a certain, I'm going to use the word we had been outfoxed.

289
00:53:09,000 --> 00:53:20,000
We had been made to look a bit chagrin and that the establishment was fully in charge.

290
00:53:20,000 --> 00:53:31,000
They were able to say that you were making false claims or you're not stating the truth in your accusations and so forth.

291
00:53:31,000 --> 00:53:56,000
So we had to counter that and at the same time the pressures from the national office and the regional office of the NAACP had started seeing you are generating more heat than we are prepared to deal with.

292
00:53:56,000 --> 00:54:17,000
So it meant that various lawsuits and at least public exposure to the media that the city had betrayed us and that the Quadricentennial Committee celebrating the anniversary and everything else.

293
00:54:17,000 --> 00:54:25,000
And we had considered filing a lawsuit to try to stop the usage of the federal warrants and all.

294
00:54:25,000 --> 00:54:37,000
So it meant that we were getting a bit too large for our bridges.

295
00:54:37,000 --> 00:54:47,000
So did that news come to you by telephone typically your phone would ring and it would be Ruby Hurley or someone else passing on that kind of.

296
00:54:47,000 --> 00:54:52,000
She made she made visits.

297
00:54:52,000 --> 00:55:13,000
And we had dinner at the various we had a restaurant right across the street from my office at that time and that restaurant was a godsend because Mr. Pennington was the owner and the operator.

298
00:55:13,000 --> 00:55:28,000
And he had an arrangement with me that any of the demonstrators anybody who came in town and was connected with Dr. Robert B. Hayling and the youth movement and all could go and get a meal.

299
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:45,000
He had world famous they custom made their ice creams using peaches and bananas and fresh fruit and everything else so the ice cream was world famous and all.

300
00:55:45,000 --> 00:55:54,000
And he would come had a routine at the end of the day and wrap them back on my door at the office Dr. Robert B. Hayling yes.

301
00:55:54,000 --> 00:56:11,000
I fed six people and we had dinners and this and that no okay Mr. Mim coming near me a chance and we issued him a check or cash money for whatever he had contributed at that time.

302
00:56:11,000 --> 00:56:40,000
At this point I also want to give thanks to the Elks members because they eventually made a facility on the second floor of what then was known as the Elks rest on all available to us for meetings and for conferences because we had a large portion of the media people gathering then.

303
00:56:40,000 --> 00:56:53,000
And the TV camera people and all gathering because they had to have an area to set up their cameras and what had you know how did the how did the members okay.

304
00:56:53,000 --> 00:57:20,000
How did the young members of the youth council how did they respond after the episodes you've described with the big dinner and Johnson's visit and the out foxing and how did you manage your relationship with them what was the character of that relationship.

305
00:57:20,000 --> 00:57:36,000
What was your role how did you own advisor unfold well it was a dual head movement and that none of the youth were involved in the negotiations and none of the youth were involved in attending the dinners.

306
00:57:36,000 --> 00:58:05,000
At that time I had acquired the support and I guess the collaboration of Mr. Henry Twine Mr. Oscar Turner or Mr. Clyde Jenkins I would have and I think even then initially I think Reverend Rev. Thomas A. Wright Sr was still in town and many of us it ended up that we had six or eight.

307
00:58:05,000 --> 00:58:34,000
Or eight members could be relied upon to be spokesperson and attend meetings and conferences and all because now we had on paper the request for the biracial committee and we had enumerated things like allowing blacks to take the fireman's examination allowing blacks to take the police examination.

308
00:58:34,000 --> 00:58:46,000
So that they could either qualify or began to make arrangements to see if they could gain employment in those various departments.

309
00:58:46,000 --> 00:58:59,000
At that time other than in janitorial and made service no blacks worked at city hall and all and even with the county administration the same was the thing.

310
00:58:59,000 --> 00:59:22,000
So we had done our homework on the actual local situation and therefore we presented them with the facts that as we saw it and very few ever bothered to count those facts or presentations that we made.

311
00:59:22,000 --> 00:59:41,000
But and the young people never demanded that they be intimately involved they were content apparently to allow the senior citizens and we would almost say like property owners and prominent people of the area.

312
00:59:41,000 --> 01:00:10,000
Now in the meantime the establishment had notified all the black school teachers and also notified Dr. Perrier and all that because at that time the school the college had 300 to 400 full time and part time students plus a staff for why would say 50 to 100 part time students.

313
01:00:10,000 --> 01:00:39,000
Part time and full time faculty members if we could have corral that type of human energetic power we wouldn't have needed any outside help but they cut us off at the knees and that all of these people were instructed that they were not to be involved or they would be in the office.

314
01:00:39,000 --> 01:01:07,000
So they would be in real trouble and that threat was so truthful that many people were totally fearful to the point that they contributed I think under the table but there was no outward showing of support and even many of the young people.

315
01:01:07,000 --> 01:01:36,000
We had college students who broke ranks and came with us who were literally threatened by their instructors because they had to make make up work and work and exams that were administered on certain days one or two instructors almost refused and we had to let them know that if they did not give this person make up work and so forth.

316
01:01:37,000 --> 01:02:06,000
The school would be in jeopardy of a lawsuit and what have you know so we had several battles going on and we had junior law students and law aids but we were able to acquire the services of a Tobias Simon out of Miami who was ACLU attorney and a tremendous fireball civil rights activist.

317
01:02:07,000 --> 01:02:31,000
He was taken away from us all too soon. He participated in the Boston Marathons and had a very credible time and everything else and all and within a day or two after completing that race and all he suffered a heart and died.

318
01:02:31,000 --> 01:02:52,000
Can you tell me about how you responded in the summer of 63 as the momentum heated up on the occasion when some students went downtown and were arrested and what would lead to the hearing in front of Judge (Charles) Mathis?

319
01:02:52,000 --> 01:03:18,000
Well in the meantime we also had a prominent senior Augustine fellow who was a student in North Carolina. I'm going to say NC A&T but I would stand corrected if it's not but I know it was an end his name was Hank Thomas Hank Thomas.

320
01:03:18,000 --> 01:03:39,000
Before I go further to say he has since gone on to become an extreme entrepreneur" owns two or three McDonalds in Atlanta and two or three Marriott hotels and so we are very proud of Hank Thomas.

321
01:03:39,000 --> 01:04:08,000
And it happened in Freedom Rider and was a Freedom Rider and all but he even did a one man sit in at one of the drug stores and all and was arrested and his bond was a hundred dollars and at that time that was a big bond and through the great line and all.

322
01:04:08,000 --> 01:04:31,000
The NAACP let it be known that Sammy Davis Jr. had put up the hundred dollar bond to get Hank Thomas out of jail but also part of the instructions from the local establishment was get him out of town.

323
01:04:31,000 --> 01:05:00,000
So after he was released he had to leave in Augustine and all but at least the movement had been started because the word came throughout the community and all that Hank Thomas had been arrested and retained overnight but was released after the NAACP had been arrested.

324
01:05:01,000 --> 01:05:30,000
It's posted the hundred dollar bond and so but the tie in that we did not know at the time of Sammy Davis Jr. and putting up the bond money and all and we had to escalate our movement in that the young people got tired of coming and being instructed in nonviolence and having

325
01:05:30,000 --> 01:05:59,000
conferences and presentations and all because they became conscious of the newspaper publicity and so forth and many of them didn't take newspapers at home so whenever we came across articles and news of interest and all we made sure that all the members attending our various youth movements had access to that bit of information

326
01:05:59,000 --> 01:06:27,000
because many of them had parents and family members working throughout the community so various people had relationships with as we heard yesterday and all Mrs. (Gwendolyn) Duncan mentioned that Mayor Shelley who was a practicing physician was her family physician and all.

327
01:06:27,000 --> 01:06:50,000
And even I admit Mayor Shelley at various medical and dental conferences and meetings and that I had been accepted to the local dental association and had gained active membership and all as the first.

328
01:06:50,000 --> 01:07:17,000
And that through the local membership quite qualified me for state membership so I was able to obtain the rank of the first African American dentist admitted to the local county state chapter of the American dental association with full membership and privileges.

329
01:07:17,000 --> 01:07:43,000
Others I think in black dentists in various locations it been kind of me honorary membership but not practicing but as luck would also have it the dental association rotated their positions in the organization

330
01:07:43,000 --> 01:08:12,000
and when it came time for election of officers I went to that meeting but apparently enough pressure had been put on the dentist that they said the meeting had been canceled and all because I would have been in line since it was a rotating on position in whatever if they had allowed me to vote at that time and get in line.

331
01:08:13,000 --> 01:08:42,000
I could have moved up and they had envisioned over a period of time I could have ascended to full presidency or leadership of the local chapter in organization so that meeting was canceled and I think by then it had become known that they had created kind of a misstep or sand.

332
01:08:42,000 --> 01:09:06,000
And at various times I knew about the other meetings by other dentists calling me saying are you coming to the meeting tonight and I would have to say is there a meeting in whatever the secretary hadn't called my secretary to tell me that we would be meeting.

333
01:09:06,000 --> 01:09:11,000
Excuse me just once I saw that's positive. We're back.

334
01:09:11,000 --> 01:09:28,000
In September of 63 the clan scheduled a major rally and you and some others had a very faithful day I wonder if you could describe that day and what happened.

335
01:09:28,000 --> 01:09:57,000
Yes the local clan chapter apparently I think they call it cladden had been all downtown passing out hand bills announcing this big clan rally and people traveling up and down US one had seen over a period of time over in a field that they were erecting this gigantic cladden.

336
01:09:58,000 --> 01:10:21,000
Across and all and this were and I guess they were putting out chairs or benches of what had been but a clan leader by the name of Connie Lynch out of California was coming to be the main speaker at this rally.

337
01:10:21,000 --> 01:10:44,000
And also I must admit that the other clan leaders like J.B. Stoner out of Atlanta and all they had called in the big guns of the clan movement to come in to do what they had to do to put a damper on this St. Augustine movement.

338
01:10:44,000 --> 01:11:13,000
And so we felt so moved that we would go out that night and thought that we would not be in in fringing on the movement or on the clan rally anything to park along US one on the roadside that we could look over into where the clan rally and everything else was being held.

339
01:11:14,000 --> 01:11:42,000
Before we knew anything after we parked and stopped they knew the car you know and they were for us of James Jackson of Mister house and James house and and clad Jenkins and myself.

340
01:11:42,000 --> 01:12:09,000
When we looked up there were clansmen with guns in the front of the car and in the rear of the car and house was driving the car and he thought he knew a side road or whatever we were thinking to escape.

341
01:12:10,000 --> 01:12:38,000
And he took a side road and lo and behold the clan had dug a moat a ditch across the roadway and we had to come to our stop to keep from going into that ditch and when we knew anything we were surrounded by clansmen ordered out of the car.

342
01:12:38,000 --> 01:13:04,000
And all and the physical punishment started at that time and they took our wallets and you know personal effects and in my wallet they sold my identity and everything else and also discovered an end of the CP card.

343
01:13:04,000 --> 01:13:31,000
And therefore that was the and the stand the impetus for them to really start beating us the beating was so severe with ax handles and baseball bats and all that we were ushered up to and eventually on stage of the where the speaker was.

344
01:13:31,000 --> 01:13:58,000
And we were piled on top of each other semi conscious like cordwood on top of each other on the stage on the stage and by then the violence was so that many of the clan attendees had started leaving the area and everything else and rather than chaining I think chaining

345
01:13:58,000 --> 01:14:27,000
and Episcopal priest of Daytona Beach had infiltrated the group and wore a personal recorder and had been able to record the speakers and everything going on at the clan rally but he saw how this thing was escalating and he back out of the meeting and everything got to his car.

346
01:14:28,000 --> 01:14:57,000
And went to a pay phone and called telehassy the highway patrol in telehassy and reported what was happening at this clan rally and what he saw and everything else and the state got on and I think they possibly called L.O. Davis and the law enforcement and in Augustine and all and they started sending in auxiliary and also support people and everything else.

347
01:14:58,000 --> 01:15:27,000
And so the powers that be knew that outside law enforcement was coming in because the announcer had on the microphone had announced if any of them had ever had the privilege of smelling a nigger burn and I guess the answer came back no or something well for those who have not had that privilege when so and so when he called the name of the person involved returns with the name of the person.

348
01:15:28,000 --> 01:15:51,000
I guess he meant some excellent but he may have mentioned gasoline that he had sent somebody to get they would be treated to the privilege of smelling niggers burn because it was his intent or stated intent that they were going to douse us with gasoline and set us on fire.

349
01:15:51,000 --> 01:16:20,000
But by that time things had degenerated so that people were fleeing and I can't say when the auxiliary policeman arrived or who broke up the meeting or what had it but fate would have it that we were rescued and put in accommodations to be taken immediately to the hospital.

350
01:16:21,000 --> 01:16:50,000
And even at the hospital we were not comfortable going to Flagler Hospital that was the local hospital so we were only treated in the emergency rooms and all and then the local mortician E.G. Chase made his hearse available to us as an ambulance to take us to Brewster Hospital.

351
01:16:51,000 --> 01:17:17,000
And Jacksonville were we were treated by black physicians and felt more comfortable because that was the black hospital in Jacksonville but we knew at that time we would not be I guess have chance to be double crossed or mistreated by clans or clans sympathizers.

352
01:17:17,000 --> 01:17:21,000
So you were very badly injured and you described injuries a little bit?

353
01:17:21,000 --> 01:17:36,000
Well I usually summarize by saying that the injuries I encountered I would take to my grief.

354
01:17:36,000 --> 01:18:05,000
So because I had his injuries I lost 11 teeth and my health right home was because my patients and all were in attendance at the clan rally.

355
01:18:05,000 --> 01:18:34,000
I can distinctly remember somebody say maybe I read it in Mr. Cheney's because he wrote a tremendous resume of his experience but they pointed out that I was a right handed dentist and they made sure that they did tremendous damage to my right arm and all.

356
01:18:34,000 --> 01:18:52,000
If I had not been in certain physical condition to rehabilitate the muscles and the ligaments in this arm I would have had to quit my practice.

357
01:18:52,000 --> 01:19:20,000
So it's the kind of thing that I don't ever like to emphasize that or make like that allowed me to become a rebel or at least was justification for the so-called militancy that I required or something and so forth.

358
01:19:20,000 --> 01:19:45,000
I thought by serving in the Air Force as an honorable recruit and volunteer and giving four years of my life and going all the way through Officer Candidate School at least allowed me to acquire full citizenship.

359
01:19:45,000 --> 01:20:04,000
But I found out that that even that did not allow me to participate and to practice the rights and privileges of the average American white citizen.

360
01:20:04,000 --> 01:20:30,000
So that was a setback in my line of thought and that no one ever could have accused me well it went so far as I have read now you know resume of L.O. Davis saying that the community decided that I was a communist and all of those things and so forth.

361
01:20:30,000 --> 01:20:55,000
Well the leader of the clan was a convicted moon channel Hoss Manucy and is still not known at this time whether Hoss Manucy had ever gone through the rights and privileges of having his citizenship restored because he had done time in federal pen for moon shining.

362
01:20:55,000 --> 01:21:23,000
I could not instill can't equate equal leadership and what he has here's Air Force officer and a citizen of good character and all leading a movement and he is a convicted moon China and all a person of questionable character and all leading a movement and these way he equated its equals.

363
01:21:23,000 --> 01:21:43,000
And the sheriff and all Hoss Manucy were very very close so that the sheriff deputized many of the clan members as auxiliary deputies of his department.

364
01:21:43,000 --> 01:22:02,000
Tell me about how you thought your way through at the end of 63 to step away from the NAACP and turn your attention towards SCLC as possible allies in this effort.

365
01:22:02,000 --> 01:22:28,000
We had run into the in other words we had ruffled the feathers of the complete NAACP national establishment to the point that Roy Wilkins was the president or CEO he was the big haunchel situated in New York City.

366
01:22:28,000 --> 01:22:47,000
And I received several calls at my office from his office and at times he came online or something but they attempted to give instructions to us as to how the movement should move forward.

367
01:22:47,000 --> 01:23:06,000
And I remember distinctly telling him or one of the secateurs of somebody involved that if they had anyone throughout the country that they thought could do a better job of leading this St. Augustine movement send them on down.

368
01:23:06,000 --> 01:23:19,000
But as long as I was on the scene and all and head of the movement I was going to do what I thought was best for the movement and for me.

369
01:23:19,000 --> 01:23:29,000
And so that meant that I had broken ranks and was not willing to take instructions from above.

370
01:23:29,000 --> 01:23:45,000
And so in a day or two later a call came from Mr. Wilkins and I answered the phone and talked with him we were very courteous with each other and has the weather down there and everything else and whatever.

371
01:23:45,000 --> 01:23:59,000
And he mentioned that if we were not prepared to follow instructions and everything from the NAACP the NAACP was prepared to withdraw our charter.

372
01:23:59,000 --> 01:24:04,000
And this was like I'm going to say it to the old Wednesday.

373
01:24:04,000 --> 01:24:26,000
And so without thinking and without even getting permission from the my local support group or even the youth group I said Mr. Wilkins when will you will you be in your office on Saturday.

374
01:24:26,000 --> 01:24:30,000
And he wanted to know what does that have to do with anything.

375
01:24:30,000 --> 01:24:40,000
I say because my feelings are at this time the mailman will bring you your charter.

376
01:24:40,000 --> 01:25:09,000
In other words in the new telling me we're fired I'm saying we resign and I packaged up through Mrs. Elizabeth Hawthorne and all and sent a mail special delivery the charter with a return receipt to New York to let them know that we were going to go on with what we were doing.

377
01:25:09,000 --> 01:25:21,000
And so we were doing what we were doing in Augustine as best we could without their support because we thought what we were doing was required.

378
01:25:21,000 --> 01:25:29,000
This is after Birmingham AL + Selma AL and all you've seen a lot of national surprise landscape by that point and you wanted to go a different direction.

379
01:25:29,000 --> 01:25:37,000
Tell me about how and we were able to mention at the time that we had been double crossed.

380
01:25:37,000 --> 01:25:45,000
Tell me about your decision and how you pursued the relationship that would unfold with Dr. King and SCLC.

381
01:25:45,000 --> 01:26:03,000
It was there that in other words we were out there up the creek without a paddle because on weekends I made trips to Atlanta and naturally trying to carry practice on in the middle of the way.

382
01:26:03,000 --> 01:26:27,000
I think Saturdays and Sundays for sure I was in Atlanta and I made visits with people like Julian Bond, all of the SNCC people, the names, SNCC, student nonviolent court and meeting committee and even met the house mother, (Ella) Baker.

383
01:26:27,000 --> 01:26:43,000
I got to know them and everything else. Then on another weekend and all I got to know people who knew Daddy King" and members of Ebenezer Baptist Church and all.

384
01:26:43,000 --> 01:26:57,000
I couldn't share with the certainty that I met either Dr. King on a passing visit or even Ebeneath on a passing visit.

385
01:26:57,000 --> 01:27:17,000
At that time, CK Steele was in the leadership of the board or whatever SCLC and he had been a tremendous supporter and he helped me make various contacts and everything else for my visit.

386
01:27:17,000 --> 01:27:31,000
Nobody wanted to pick up a trouble making chapter and a renegade group that could cause them trouble.

387
01:27:31,000 --> 01:27:44,000
It was pointed out that Selma and Birmingham AL + Selma AL and all of these areas had been so severe and SNCC was heavily involved in Mississippi and all.

388
01:27:44,000 --> 01:28:13,000
It had almost been fought to a standstill, brought to a standstill and I'm going ahead of myself but when it came time for the passage of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, Lyndon (B.) Johnson, now who had with the Kennedy's murder and assassination had moved from vice president to president.

389
01:28:14,000 --> 01:28:37,000
He had the good graces of the civil rights organization that he wanted two weeks of cessation of demonstrations and Dr. King and the powers that had agreed and other organizations had agreed.

390
01:28:37,000 --> 01:28:55,000
We had been double crossed several times in all and when it came down to the St. Augustine chapter, we said, fool me once, shame on you, fool me twice, shame on me.

391
01:28:55,000 --> 01:29:05,000
We said we were not going to stop demonstrating until the Civil Rights Act of 1964 had been signed.

392
01:29:05,000 --> 01:29:22,000
They had to speed up the signing and everything else and we have checked our records now because I had made statements that Dr. King left St. Augustine and went to Washington for the signing of the Civil Rights Act of 1964.

393
01:29:22,000 --> 01:29:36,000
But I can say with certainty now that on June 30, 1964, he was in St. Augustine and the Civil Rights Act of 1964 was signed Civil Rights Act of 1964.

394
01:29:36,000 --> 01:29:59,000
But he would have had to go to Atlanta or to Daytona to catch a plane to get to Washington so some daylight times intervened so please don't hold me to the quote of leaving exact St. Augustine to get to Washington for Civil Rights Act of 1964.

395
01:29:59,000 --> 01:30:05,000
Dr. King would first come to St. Augustine himself in May of 64.

396
01:30:05,000 --> 01:30:16,000
But prior to that point, you had mentioned that you had developed a very close relationship with the folks in the SNCC office in Atlanta.

397
01:30:16,000 --> 01:30:23,000
You had obviously planned Freedom Summer for 64 and you planned something for the spring break period.

398
01:30:23,000 --> 01:30:24,000
Yes.

399
01:30:24,000 --> 01:30:29,000
Can you describe that for St. Augustine? It was very interesting and led to all kinds of interesting developments.

400
01:30:29,000 --> 01:30:49,000
Rev. William Sloane Coffin Jr, who was involved with the Yale Divinity School, had contacted us and allowed us to end Revan Robinson to develop a relationship.

401
01:30:49,000 --> 01:31:18,000
And they had recruited between the Yale students that, rather than to take a spring break and go to the beaches and all, they would come to St. Augustine and conduct a tutorial program and clean up, fix up, paint up, or whatever needed to be done for about a two weeks period to lend their support to the Civil Rights Act of 1964.

402
01:31:18,000 --> 01:31:33,000
Activity of St. Augustine. That was a coup. That was a publicity dream that we never could have concocted on our own.

403
01:31:33,000 --> 01:31:45,000
Did that come through SNCC or did that come from the folks at the say Rev. William Sloane Coffin Jr knowing through press reports about St. Augustine? How was that connection for?

404
01:31:45,000 --> 01:31:50,000
I don't think we had the support of a national organization.

405
01:31:50,000 --> 01:32:00,000
Because those students and their families and everything raised the monies to get them here and everything else on their own.

406
01:32:00,000 --> 01:32:14,000
But now we also had a setup as I told you through the feeding setup and all that the people who came to us, we gave them at least breakfast, lunch, lunch, and dinner.

407
01:32:14,000 --> 01:32:29,000
Many times we were used as a peanut butter and jelly and cheese and a fruit, apple or an orange and usually a cold drink.

408
01:32:29,000 --> 01:32:37,000
And then they had the rights to go to Mr. Pendman's restaurant and order a meal or whatever they wanted.

409
01:32:37,000 --> 01:32:45,000
So what was the name of that restaurant? I'm going to say the Freeze or I would have...

410
01:32:45,000 --> 01:32:48,000
Yes, and I would get the full name.

411
01:32:48,000 --> 01:32:49,000
I will not double check.

412
01:32:49,000 --> 01:32:50,000
Yes.

413
01:32:50,000 --> 01:33:05,000
So after that spring break season when a number of Northern white college students came to town, the momentum was really accelerating towards May and June.

414
01:33:05,000 --> 01:33:25,000
Well, the reason I said the publicity crew, many of the participants who came, we had white male and females who had never been exposed to black families and see in St. Augustine to their credit.

415
01:33:25,000 --> 01:33:32,000
Many of the black families agreed to house these volunteers in their homes.

416
01:33:32,000 --> 01:33:41,000
So they had a chance to meet these people at the various church functions and all they met people and everything else.

417
01:33:41,000 --> 01:33:50,000
And also in the meantime, somewhere along the line, Dr. King had participated in a rally in Tallahassee and all.

418
01:33:50,000 --> 01:33:59,000
And we made a trip, Mr. Twine, and a group of us made a trip from St. Augustine to be in Tallahassee for that full day.

419
01:33:59,000 --> 01:34:10,000
And so I had a chance, fleetingly, to talk to Dr. King and other support members of SCLC and so forth.

420
01:34:10,000 --> 01:34:11,000
Yeah.

421
01:34:11,000 --> 01:34:33,000
I would love to spend time talking about your perspective on how the specifics of the relationship with Dr. King and SCLCs, you worked out the events of May and June.

422
01:34:34,000 --> 01:35:02,000
See, this weekend trips here escalated and that I made trips into New York to Boston and all of those areas and made visits to Harvard and MIT and other various Esther Burgess who was a husband.

423
01:35:02,000 --> 01:35:13,000
Bishop John Melville Burgess was the first black episcopal bishop in the United States and he covered an area in the Massachusetts area and all.

424
01:35:13,000 --> 01:35:21,000
So we had developed through meetings and forums and all a relationship with various people.

425
01:35:21,000 --> 01:35:41,000
And also I wanted to point out that many of the students who came from Yale went back and they even developed a drama, a stage play and everything to drama to dramatize their experience in St. Augustine.

426
01:35:41,000 --> 01:35:54,000
And somebody played L.O. Davis and somebody played Judge (Charles) Mathis and the entire thing that they presented throughout the New Haven community and all.

427
01:35:54,000 --> 01:36:11,000
And they had influential parents who eventually sent us financial support and all because it is known and has been known St. Augustine could not carry the movement financially and what had been.

428
01:36:11,000 --> 01:36:40,000
So we had to have outside support and with the people from Yale and the people from the Boston area because I think you know that Esther Burgess, Mrs. Rowe, whose husband was in the industrialist, millionaire, Mrs. Campbell, whose husband was an industrialist.

429
01:36:40,000 --> 01:37:09,000
And she was a millionaire from that area and Mary Peabody of the infamous Peabody family and all came to St. Augustine and many other dignitaries who gave us support including Alvarus attorneys and everything else and what had been done.

430
01:37:09,000 --> 01:37:25,000
Everything else and what had agreed to speak and conduct rallies including Jackie Robinson and all but they were not consenting to be arrested and definitely did not consent to go to Yale.

431
01:37:25,000 --> 01:37:29,000
Tell me if you would just for the tape who Mrs. Peabody was.

432
01:37:29,000 --> 01:37:46,000
The mother of the sitting governor, Endicott "Chub" Peabody, Charles Peabody, or the state of Massachusetts and she was the matron of the 72 years of age of the Peabody clan.

433
01:37:46,000 --> 01:38:05,000
I mean it's really a testament I think to your capacity to develop all these powerful relationships because as you say as the record shows you were successful in I mean Peabody spent a couple nights in local jail in St. Augustine as the governor, as the mother of the sitting governor of Massachusetts.

434
01:38:05,000 --> 01:38:11,000
I was arrested with her at the Monson Motor Lodge.

435
01:38:11,000 --> 01:38:14,000
She's a motor love restaurant.

436
01:38:14,000 --> 01:38:24,000
Which is actually I'll just say for the tape it's where this building we're in now stands the hotel having been demolished and replaced by this structure.

437
01:38:24,000 --> 01:38:32,000
I'm just in interest of time we have probably about 10 minutes left and I'm sorry that you may be right.

438
01:38:32,000 --> 01:38:37,000
Please. We have to drive over to Gainesville.

439
01:38:37,000 --> 01:38:53,000
I want to expect two final things. One is just to have you reflect a little bit more on the relationship of all that you did here in its culmination in late June through June and the signing in DC of the Civil Rights Act of 1964.

440
01:38:53,000 --> 01:39:01,000
Just how you think about the relation of the one to the other as you look back.

441
01:39:01,000 --> 01:39:17,000
St. Augustine. I hate to say never ever admitted.

442
01:39:17,000 --> 01:39:26,000
I'm going to say the general citizenry of St. Augustine in that James Brock died.

443
01:39:26,000 --> 01:39:39,000
On the Monson Motor Lodge had the infamous picture of him putting acid in the water with the freedom demonstrators in the water in the pool.

444
01:39:39,000 --> 01:39:46,000
And that picture went all the way around the world. I understand in Russia,

445
01:39:46,000 --> 01:39:59,000
the news paper had him on the front page of the newspaper putting acid in the water when human beings were in the swimming pool.

446
01:39:59,000 --> 01:40:09,000
But he went to his grave and unrequited uncompromised segregationists.

447
01:40:09,000 --> 01:40:17,000
We have since met his daughter. I didn't meet her personally. She has moved from St. Augustine to North Carolina somewhere now.

448
01:40:17,000 --> 01:40:28,000
But she mentioned that she went to high school with black students and all and that she did not retain the same attitude as her father.

449
01:40:28,000 --> 01:40:37,000
But he literally took George Wallace type segregationist yesterday.

450
01:40:37,000 --> 01:40:46,000
Segregationist tomorrow. So segregationist for life.

451
01:40:46,000 --> 01:40:53,000
Tell me about your decision.

452
01:40:53,000 --> 01:41:02,000
I would not be here.

453
01:41:02,000 --> 01:41:16,000
Well, it was a dual type thing in that I had five years to give to the state of Florida to pay for the tuition help that they had given me in dental school.

454
01:41:16,000 --> 01:41:31,000
After five years in a location that they designated because as I told you, they had consented that St. Augustine or Panama City Florida would have satisfied their requirement

455
01:41:31,000 --> 01:41:38,000
and that it was an area of need for a black dentist. So by staying here those five years I paid back the state.

456
01:41:38,000 --> 01:41:51,000
And then also an opportunity had arisen in Cocoa, Florida, Florida which is right next to Cape Kennedy and all.

457
01:41:51,000 --> 01:42:18,000
And I went down and met the local citizens there and developed a friendship of the black mortician, Rudy Stone, who gave me a living facilities and all and helped open the doors through the black churches of Cocoa, Florida to me coming in and opening a practice.

458
01:42:18,000 --> 01:42:27,000
And right away because of the workers at the Cape, my practice took off even though it was a makeshift office.

459
01:42:27,000 --> 01:42:47,000
We were in an elks building and I was next door to a black physician Dr. Jerkins who was an older man but he had a practice going and he helped by referring patients to me and coming as his family and so forth.

460
01:42:47,000 --> 01:43:14,000
And it was wonderful but Lyndon B. Johnson caught us again and that the main heart of that whole establishment at Cape Kennedy was the control center and because of the electronic era the control center could be anywhere.

461
01:43:14,000 --> 01:43:25,000
And he intervened and had the control center with all that big payroll move to Johnson Space Center.

462
01:43:25,000 --> 01:43:35,000
Was there besides the opportunity that Cocoa, Florida presented?

463
01:43:35,000 --> 01:43:42,000
Were there dimensions of your decision that touched on all that you've gone through here and the implications for your family and such?

464
01:43:42,000 --> 01:43:48,000
Or was it exclusively a professional choice to go to Cocoa, Florida?

465
01:43:48,000 --> 01:44:12,000
Professional and also the relationship with Rudy Stone and the people that I met there and then a younger and educated environment because many of my patients starting all worked at the Cape and many were technicians and other scientists involved with NASA and everything else.

466
01:44:12,000 --> 01:44:38,000
In fact several of my patients ended up being connected to the astronaut families because my dentist, my family dentist in Tallahassee Dr. Campbell had offered through my mother to tell Robert to come on to Tallahassee and he can either practice with me or I will give him my practice in Tallahassee.

467
01:44:38,000 --> 01:44:51,000
But as I said at the time I just didn't give complete thought because it would have been more economical for me at the cost in moving.

468
01:44:51,000 --> 01:45:06,000
Because my brother had put in four years in the Air Force and had moved back to Tallahassee now and was housekeeping in Tallahassee and my family had a big house, four bedroom house and everything.

469
01:45:06,000 --> 01:45:13,000
And we grew up in and there would have been accommodations for me and my family.

470
01:45:13,000 --> 01:45:29,000
But I chose Cocoa, Florida and bought a two bedroom house and I thought that by buying the three bedroom house next door.

471
01:45:29,000 --> 01:45:53,000
My plans were to join those two houses but I found out that was in violation of cold in that you can only have one water meter to a house and therefore I was diminishing the second water meter without proper authorization.

472
01:45:53,000 --> 01:46:08,000
So we commuted, the kids went from a house to house, the main house and then back to the other house but we never made a union or a junction there because it was illegal.

473
01:46:08,000 --> 01:46:17,000
Was it easier, final thought? Was it easier to think for your children to come up and Cocoa, Florida than hear after all that happened here?

474
01:46:17,000 --> 01:46:44,000
With my right being a school teacher with a master's degree in biology and all, I have to give her credit for all that my kids attained and did and that they were, I guess, compatible with whatever went on in the family and that they were all good scholars.

475
01:46:44,000 --> 01:46:58,000
And excellent leaders and so forth. And I guess since time is a factor. I had the good fortune and I'm just coming down from cloud nine.

476
01:46:58,000 --> 01:47:27,000
The city of St. Augustine gave me the Award of Valor on Civil Rights Act of 1964 and presented this award to me with the mayor and at least three commissioners and one or two other city officials present at our ACCORD where Dorothy Cotton spoke from her.

477
01:47:27,000 --> 01:47:42,000
From her affiliation with SCLC and Dr. King and we honored the Rev. Goldie Eubanks family with the Dr. Hale and award of valor.

478
01:47:42,000 --> 01:48:10,000
We give a Waterford Crystal eagle-in-flight symbol and it's inscribed as the recipient requests or designates and the you banks family, many of Reverend you banks his siblings came and extended family members and all.

479
01:48:10,000 --> 01:48:27,000
Because I saw those young people grow up as teenagers and all and now we're at the point that many pursued successful careers including school teaching and all and had now reached age of retirement.

480
01:48:27,000 --> 01:48:39,000
And my daughter youngest daughter who was a graduate of Yale crystal and MBA from Stanford came with her husband Chris.

481
01:48:39,000 --> 01:49:07,000
The fair who is Princeton grad and Harvard Business School grad and he is an employee of Apple Inc and the Far East branch and they came from Singapore or their vacation to be present at the event of the presentation and brought my two grandsons.

482
01:49:07,000 --> 01:49:33,000
Roman who is eight years of age at that time and Avery who was six so that complete weekend July the second old 11 has been an experience for me because my oldest daughter and her husband Robin and David came from Mississippi.

483
01:49:33,000 --> 01:49:51,000
My youngest sister and Evonne and her husband came from Sarasota and I had many other extended family members to come from afar to be with me so it was a real celebration.

484
01:49:51,000 --> 01:50:16,000
Let me say it's just a final word I know that even now your work continues you're still active with with with ACCORD with miss Vickers and I think you're meeting with a bunch of folks tonight as you continue efforts here to help continue to improve the city so it's been a great privilege and pleasure to be with you.

485
01:50:16,000 --> 01:50:28,000
I hope we're still recording because I don't think I gave emphasis to the establishment of the freedom for the foot soldiers.

486
01:50:28,000 --> 01:50:40,000
We were let me have you say word about that we were happy of course to have the conversation yesterday with Mrs. Barbara (Edna) Vickers.

487
01:50:40,000 --> 01:51:08,000
You wanted to say a final note about about Mrs. Barbara (Edna) Vickers and Mrs. Barbara (Edna) Vickers who was my neighbor from across the street on it was Scott Street then now is Dr. Hayling Place the street was named for me on June 20, 2003.

488
01:51:08,000 --> 01:51:37,000
I forgive me of 03 June the 20th of 03 and my daughter and her husband came from California at the time they were living in San Mateo and brought my six seven month old son Roman grandson in the baby carriage and the stroller and all to be present for the street naming him.

489
01:51:37,000 --> 01:52:04,000
We had 21 hailings for the street naming ceremony and part of the activity was moved up and that they had mentioned and especially Commissioner Earl Jones that most cities had pay tribute to their leaders in abstenture after they had passed.

490
01:52:04,000 --> 01:52:25,000
He wanted to try to give me this honor while I was still able to smell the roses and so forth and so there was a tremendous tribute and that Earl Jones's mother Mrs. Maddie Jones had been an assistant to me for about three years or more.

491
01:52:25,000 --> 01:52:54,000
Such a brave lady because she came to work every day stayed and supported me when many of my patients many of my friends and others were afraid I was like a leper in that person with leper in that I was to be avoided and that my office would possibly be shot up or dynamited.

492
01:52:55,000 --> 01:53:09,000
And everything if they were there they would have been involved but Mrs. Jones came and stayed as long and as late as we needed to to have the office open and so forth.

493
01:53:09,000 --> 01:53:11,000
Can I ask you to share the sign?

494
01:53:11,000 --> 01:53:13,000
Yes.

495
01:53:13,000 --> 01:53:34,000
I am so proud to present this sign and I bring it with me to all the meetings and we have a ceremony where the various people involved have to come up and touch the sign and try to say which portion of this sign that they helped earn and qualify for.

496
01:53:34,000 --> 01:53:45,000
So it's a little routine and that's the reason I have this with me that we do it and wherever the activists people have gathered we give them an offer.

497
01:53:45,000 --> 01:53:58,000
I did not bring the citation and all because it's in case in a glass in case and therefore we would have been subjecting it to break it and everything so I decided not to bring it in the car.

498
01:53:58,000 --> 01:54:04,000
Could you lift it up just to about that screen? Let me just focus on it.

499
01:54:04,000 --> 01:54:07,000
You can smile.

500
01:54:07,000 --> 01:54:09,000
That's great.

501
01:54:09,000 --> 01:54:11,000
Dr. Hayling, thank you so much.

502
01:54:11,000 --> 01:54:15,000
Well please please please the honor.

503
01:54:15,000 --> 01:54:24,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
